'''Gospel Kazako''' (born 29 December 1968)<ref name=AM>[http://africanmillionaire.net/2011/09/malawi-millionaire-broadcaster-gospe/ African Millionaire online magazine, September 21, 2011: 'Behind the Success of Media Mogul Kazako']</ref> is a Malawian entrepreneur who in 2005 founded the [[Zodiak Broadcasting Station]], the most popular radio station in [[Malawi]]. He is also known as a poet.<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-14857642 BBC News 13 September 2011 'African Dream: Malawi's Gospel Kazako']</ref>

Gospel Kazako was brought up in the southern Malawian town of [[Zomba, Malawi|Zomba]], the eldest of eight children<ref name=CNN>[http://edition.cnn.com/2015/02/06/africa/gospel-kazako-zodiak-malawi/ CNN African Voices February 6, 2015: 'Video fails to kill the radio star: How to build a media empire, Malawian style']</ref> whose father was a watchman.<ref name=AM /> He attended H.H.I. Secondary School in Blantyre until 1990.<ref>[http://mwnation.com/gospel-kazako-he-has-not-changed/ The Nation online 23 February 2014: 'Gospel Kazako: He has not changed' by Adamson Muula].</ref> After obtaining a diploma in journalism, for seven years he worked at the state-owned [[Malawi Broadcasting Corporation]] (MBC),<ref name=CNN /> before leaving to form his own company to record music, soundtracks and adverts for other radio stations.<ref name=BBC /> Finally, after several attempts to obtain a licence, he opened Zodiak Broadcasting Station (ZBS) in 2005.<ref name=CNN /> Zodiak Broadcasting Station currently has over 25 transmitting sites and covers the whole of Malawi.<ref name=BBC /> The station was awarded a licence to broadcast TV in 2012.<ref>[http://www.faceofmalawi.com/2012/07/zodiak-broadcasting-station-gets-tv-license/ Face of Malawi online news, 25 July 2012]</ref>

