{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox magazine | logo = | logo_size = | image_file = | image_size = <!-- (defaults to user thumbnail size if no size is stated) --> | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = | editor_title = | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = Business magazine | frequency = Weekly | total_circulation = |circulation_year = | publisher = Kommersant Publishing House | founder = | founded = 1994 | firstdate = <!-- {{Start date|year|month|day}} --> | finaldate = January 2017 (print) | company = | country = Russia | based = [[Moscow]] | language = Russian | website = [http://www.kommersant.ru/money ''Kommersant Dengi''] | issn = | oclc = }} '''''Kommersant Dengi''''' was a weekly print business and finance magazine published in [[Moscow, Russia]]. In January 2017 the magazine became online-only publication.
==History and profile== ''Kommersant Dengi'' was established in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kommersant Dengi|url=http://www.cesanamedia.com/en/media-portfolio/search-by-location/europe/russia/kommersant-dengi/|work=Cesanamedia Italia|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> It was published by Kommersant Publishing House on a weekly basis.<ref name="pub"/> The company was owned by [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] from 1999 to 2006 and then was acquired by [[Badri Patarkatsishvili]].<ref name="ioc">{{cite journal|author=Alexei Bessudnov|title=Media map|journal=Index on Censorship|date=2008|volume=37|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/03064220701882780|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> The same year [[Alisher Usmanov]] bought the company.<ref name="ioc"/><ref name=mot>{{cite news|title=Kommersant Editor Steps Down Amid Rumors of Pressure From Above|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/news/kommersant-editor-steps-down-amid-rumors-of-pressure-from-above-41196|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=The Moscow Times|date=10 November 2014}}</ref> The magazine is headquartered in Moscow.<ref name="ewykz">{{cite book|title=The Europa World Year: Kazakhstan - Zimbabwe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gP_-8rXzQs8C&pg=PA3564|accessdate=22 April 2017|year=2004|publisher=Taylor & Francis Group|isbn=978-1-85743-255-8|page=3564}}</ref> Its sister publications include ''Kommersant Vlast'', which was formerly named ''Kommersant-Weekly'', and daily newspaper ''[[Kommersant]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Katja Lehtisaari|title=The concept of market|journal=Helda|url=https://helda.helsinki.fi/bitstream/handle/10138/136389/lethisaari.pdf?sequence=1|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> Sergei Yakovlev is among the former [[editors-in-chief]] of the magazine.<ref name=mot/>
''Kommersant Dengi'' covers articles on the analysis of [[financial market]]s, [[investments]] and practical information about financial companies.<ref name="pub">{{cite web|title=Kommersant Dengi|url=http://www.publicitas.com/austria/media-solutions/factsheet/mediadata/kommersant-dengi/?PARAM1=KMADM1|work=Publicitas|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> In 2002 the magazine sold 85,000 copies.<ref name=ewykz/> In January 2017 it was announced that the print version of the magazine closed and that it would continue as an online magazine.<ref>{{cite news|title=Media: "Kommersant" close issue print magazines "the Power" and "Money"|url=http://chelorg.com/2017/01/09/media-kommersant-close-issue-print-magazines-the-power-and-money/|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Russia News Today|date=9 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title="Kommersant" was left without paper "Money" and "Power" – Вести.Ru|url=http://greatestdiscoverytechnology.blogspot.com.tr/2017/01/kommersant-was-left-without-paper-money.html|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Greatest Discovery Technology|date=9 January 2017}}</ref>
